    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1bea06ee_e0899404",
        "filename": "grpc/prpc/server.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 339,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002539
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-13T20:34:52Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "readMessage can be slow since it does network IO, better to release the mutex before calling it:\n\n  s.mu.RLock()\n  fixFieldMasksForJSON :\u003d s.fixFieldMasksForJSON\n  s.mu.RUnlock()",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 339,
        "startChar": 13,
        "endLine": 339,
        "endChar": 24
      },
      "revId": "f162f2d3b00821d92483c0d6412c0ab2e2e38b53",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5d9e2cce_ba59fed5",
        "filename": "grpc/prpc/server.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 339,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003211
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-13T21:37:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "If that\u0027s the case then the value may be stale by the time readMessage runs. In which case, do I need to acquire the lock at all? Let it be racy. Who cares if one readMessage call goes through with the wrong value of fixFieldMasksForJSON, in practice it\u0027s set before serving anyway. In fact I\u0027ve changed it to not require a lock since you can theoretically swap Authenticator, AccessControl, and UnaryServerInterceptor at any time without a lock (see comment thread above).",
      "parentUuid": "1bea06ee_e0899404",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 339,
        "startChar": 13,
        "endLine": 339,
        "endChar": 24
      },
      "revId": "f162f2d3b00821d92483c0d6412c0ab2e2e38b53",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e433ccee_1df10a94",
        "filename": "grpc/prpc/server.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 339,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002539
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-13T22:09:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes, here this lock doesn\u0027t matter. It would have mattered more if FixFieldMasks(\u003cvalue\u003e) was called often in a background goroutine. Generally without the lock (or atomics) other goroutines could read stale value cached in their local CPU caches. Sometimes it leads to bugs, e.g. when a goroutine makes writes A and B, and assumes if other goroutines see effects of B, they also see effects of A. Without atomic or locks this may be violated.",
      "parentUuid": "5d9e2cce_ba59fed5",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 339,
        "startChar": 13,
        "endLine": 339,
        "endChar": 24
      },
